        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2822572801" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3503646174314082118">One of my favourite novels - read it countless years ago but it stills brings a smile to my face. Fay Weldon managed to take a difficult character, the physically unattractive, unloved and abandoned wife/mother and make her into a figure of ingenuity and strength, without ever making her unlovable for the reader. No mean feat because our society’s abusive and dismissive treatment of such “unwanted” women must be infuriating for an author who believes so strongly in women’s causes <br/><br/>There’s an enor</span>
  <span id="freeText3503646174314082118" style="display:none">One of my favourite novels - read it countless years ago but it stills brings a smile to my face. Fay Weldon managed to take a difficult character, the physically unattractive, unloved and abandoned wife/mother and make her into a figure of ingenuity and strength, without ever making her unlovable for the reader. No mean feat because our society’s abusive and dismissive treatment of such “unwanted” women must be infuriating for an author who believes so strongly in women’s causes <br /><br />There’s an enormous amount of fun and humour and I recall sitting on the Tube laughing out loud at the way our heroine rebuilds her life while destroying her faithless husband’s. It was a delight and definitely worth reading a second time around. It’s not just a comic novel though; it reminds us of the value of the women we choose to marginalise and often despise</span>
  <a data-text-id="3503646174314082118" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


