    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2715307498" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2715307498" />
    <a title="Realini" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7873218-realini"><img alt="Realini" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1420269105p2/7873218.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2715307498?book_show_action=true">Feb 14, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Realini" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Realini" href="/user/show/7873218-realini">Realini</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7873218-realini?shelf=humor">humor</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7873218-realini?shelf=guardian-1-000">guardian-1-000</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2715307498" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3639321370019569133">The Life and Loves of a She-Devil by Fay Weldon<br/>9 out of 10<br/><br/><br/><br/>On some levels, it is a challenge to rate, analyze, have a definite opinion about a book that seems rather complicated, with uneven chapters and forays into bizarre, otherworldly venues, which are nevertheless justified, given the She-Devil from the title.<br/>The book has been included on The Guardian 1,000 Books Everyone Must Read list and I think it is in the comedy section, for this is not a narrative about vampires, undead, although there</span>
  <span id="freeText3639321370019569133" style="display:none">The Life and Loves of a She-Devil by Fay Weldon<br />9 out of 10<br /><br /><br /><br />On some levels, it is a challenge to rate, analyze, have a definite opinion about a book that seems rather complicated, with uneven chapters and forays into bizarre, otherworldly venues, which are nevertheless justified, given the She-Devil from the title.<br />The book has been included on The Guardian 1,000 Books Everyone Must Read list and I think it is in the comedy section, for this is not a narrative about vampires, undead, although there are some ghosts which are mentioned and seen in passing and the plot is mostly extravagant and for the taste of this reader a bit - or more - absurd, surrealist than he likes his reading to be.<br /><br />In my view, some of the story is not entertaining, not even a little interesting, but this can in fact demonstrate the male limits - Fay Weldon is a feminist and part of the book is about men's shortcomings, often vile character - for I do not get why I should read so much about plastic surgery, making long legs much shorter - aren't they supposed to be desirable? Well, in this perverse male universe- stitches, moles, changing the clitoris and the resulting enhanced sexual pleasure, with too many details about what seems like a prosaic subject, good for manuals of surgery, but not for a captivating novel.<br />To some extent, that was hyperbole, for I do get why the description of the travails is needed, for we have to see the torment, torture inflicted- if at times indirectly- by the husband and then there are also interesting meditations on what the impact on the soul is, how people change after surgery, but they eventually tend to return to their shape, which is influenced by the mind and all this is interlaced with humor, albeit of a weird kind.<br /><br />Ruth Patchett is the main character, the one who becomes a She-Devil, when her husband, Bobbo - what a name, children use that for candy, an accountant starts working for a famous novelist, Mary Fisher, has an affair with her and then decides he will leave his home and children, to live in the tower, on the shore, where the writer lives in luxury, with servants, the main one is Gracia, who is once in a while her love as well.<br />Ruth is abnormally tall, she has moles on her face from where hairs grow and Bobbo had started a sexual relationship with her when they were both very young, the bond had not meant much for the man, if anything, he just found climbing into her bed cosy, warm and comfortable and when they eventually married, he talked about an open marriage, thinking he will have sex with other women and just tell his spouse about it.<br /><br />Abandoning his home, children - they have one girl, who is large, clumsy like her mother and a boy, Nicola - and wife has a tremendous impact on the heroine, who is called a she-devil by the cheating man and decides to become one, burning down the house, taking the children to the tower and the mistress of their parent, leaving them there for they have nowhere to live now.<br /><br />Payback is a very good Mel Gibson motion picture, wherein he had been cheated, made to suffer and then he comes back to extract Vengeance- with the fury expressed by Samuel L. Jackson in Pulp Fiction, when he quotes from Ezechiel 25:17 - and this sort of severe, painful retribution appears to be the only goal of the deceived woman whose only goal, meaning in life is to make Bobbo and Mary Fisher pay for their sin.<br />Therefore, she finds a job at the retirement home where Mary's mother, Pearl, is a patient and uses cunning and a ruthless plan to get the old woman on her feet, changing medication, using psychology and subliminal messages, then she packs her off to a train, calls Garcia to wait for her as she comes to visit her daughter at the tower and then she pretends to the manager of the establishment that this patient had been incontinent for months and this results in expulsion, for the scheming protagonist knows the rules...as soon as they start wetting the bed, the inmates are sent off.<br /><br />Mary Fisher was unhappy with the arrival of the children of her lover and now she has the added pain of caring for a parent that, when sedated presents one set of problems and when not on medication, she has other issues and the happiness of the rich, appreciated - by rather simple readers, for her travails wee not for the erudite- author is beginning to crumble and then disappear to make place for chagrin, suffering and terrible misfortune.<br />The She-Devil learns about accounting, breaks into the office of her husband- they are still, for he could not get a divorce and it was not clear if Ruth was still alive - and she fiddles with the accounts, transferring money to put him on the spot and eventually have the authorities charge and sentence him, pushing another woman into his arms, only to manipulate her into giving Ruth two million dollars stolen from various forgeries and then have the police incriminate the accountant.<br /><br />They know about his assistant, but not that she has disappeared under a false identity- The She-Devil paid for the fake documents and her passage to New Zealand- and the investigators assume that the woman run away with the millions that they were supposed to share, embezzled by Bobbo, who is not cooperating as they see it - the reader knows he cannot offer the whereabouts of the accomplice, for he is totally ignorant of the whole scheme.<br />To make sure that he does not get a light punishment- if we call one year in prison small beer - Ruth enters the service of the judge who will give the years for the verdict in the case, then she accepts to have sex with him and the associated sadistic preferred acts - there is some outre, jocular explanation as to the psychological medium of this and perhaps other judges -who used to inflict extreme pain on his spouse and he now can do it on the patient She-Devil.<br />Eventually, this deranged character wants to look like Mary Fisher and not just resemble her, but become an exact copy, even if that means a fortune spend on the best specialists, taking out in agony all her teeth to be replaced by others, and cutting down her extra large size, literally, by taking out large - dangerously, absurdly- portions of her femur bone, hands and other parts of her anatomy, muscles and so on.<br /><br />This is where I found it rather overbearing- again, I get the picture and see that this is about extreme pain caused by love, losing meaning and everything in the world and the excessive retaliation required by this and then we are talking about a She-Devil, not a human being anymore.<br />Nonetheless, it looked rather gratuitous and the pain appeared to be transferred towards...<br /><br />The reader!<br />It was like I need to learn about surgery, trauma, cutting bone and tissue, like I am preparing to go to medical school.<br /><br />On the other hand, all this could be construed as a needed lesson for the squeamish, oh so sensitive male chauvinist who has trouble reading what we men can do to our better halves...<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3639321370019569133" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


